  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "For example, in ASR, the pipeline typically involved a separately trained acoustic model (AM), language model (LM), and decoder, integrated via weighted finite-state transducers (WFSTs).",
    "These components were optimized independently and lacked task adaptability.",
    "Typical implementations include Gaussian Mixture Model -Hidden Markov Model (GMM-HMM) frameworks and later Deep Neural Network (DNN-HMM) hybrids [6], [45], which formed the foundation of many large-scale ASR toolkits such as Kaldi [46] and CMU Sphinx [47].",
    "This design required extensive engineering effort, heavily relied on handcrafted configurations, and lacked the capacity to integrate knowledge holistically or support multitask generalization.Moreover, in the SLU domain, spoken language understanding was conventionally built on top of ASR outputs.",
    "Early SLU systems adopted the ASR → NLU pipeline [4], [48], where natural language understanding models operated on 1-best or N-best ASR hypotheses to perform tasks such as intent classification, slot filling, and dialogue state tracking [49]."
  ],
